ring this period that the church was compelled to produce an account of the theological status of the religious image that would nevertheless not be open to even the slightest suspicion of idolatry. The solution arrived at was the dual doctrine of the image, invisible (and thus beyond the charge of idolatry) and the icon, visible, and thus perfectly fitted to be placed at the center of a pedagogical and political strategy serving the temporal power of the church. The foundations of this immense philosophical enterprise were laid in no less than the multifarious, interwoven strands of the divine economy, God's overall plan for the salvation of humanity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aArt -- Theory. 4aPhilosophy -- Political Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 7aART / Popular Culture.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361928940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503619289423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503619289/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles